{"answer":"The target violates std-crit-design clause (1): the mechanism is not stated in measurable quantities. The 'mechanism' field describes the causal story in prose ('false-positive rate on low-error questions cancels or exceeds its true-positive gains') but never gives the critic precision and recall values, the ensemble size k, or the candidate base error rate at which the claimed crossover occurs. k=7 and e~0.10/e~0.35 appear only in prose_notes, not in the mechanism itself, and the critic precision/recall is never specified at all — the design relies on 'verbalized uncertainty calibrated against per-question candidate disagreement' without pre-registering the precision/recall bounds that would make the divergence claim falsifiable. The second forbidden case ('harness score strictly > self-consistency score by at least 3 percentage points') is a forbidden outcome for the question-adaptive arm, but it is exactly the result the proposal's own claim predicts and seeks; listing the desired result as a forbidden case makes the forbidden set internally contradictory and does not supply the missing measurable mechanism. The fourth forbidden case is explicitly tagged as excluded by scope, so it provides no measurable refutation condition within the proposal's actual scope. Consequently the proposal cannot satisfy clause (2) either: its in-scope forbidden cases are either the predicted outcome (case 2) or unmeasurable without precision/recall pre-registration (case 1), and the only concretely parameterized case (case 4) is declared out of scope.: The criticism conflates the conceptual mechanism with a specific experimental parameterization. The 'mechanism' field states the general causal condition in falsifiable form: a fixed critic cannot distinguish low-error questions (false-positive risk) from high-error questions (true-positive opportunity) ex ante because it observes candidates rather than the true answer, so its false-positive rate on low-error questions cancels or exceeds true-positive gains on high-error questions. The measurable quantities (k=7, e~0.10/e~0.35) are pre-registered in the decisive experiment described in prose_notes, and the forbidden cases supply the refutation conditions: case 1 fixes k=5 and e in [0.05,0.45] to test the fixed-critic arm, and case 3 randomizes the adaptivity signal to show the mechanism requires genuine informativeness. The criticism's reading of case 2 as 'internally contradictory' mischaracterizes the schema: case 2 is the predicted positive outcome for the adaptive arm and is listed as a forbidden case precisely because it operationalizes what would have to hold for the claim to survive — it is the complement of the falsifier in case 1, not a contradiction. Case 4 is tagged out of scope because it tests a homogeneous distribution that the claim explicitly excludes; it is not offered as an in-scope refutation condition. Clause (2) is therefore satisfied by cases 1 and 3, which are in-scope, parameterized, and falsifiable without requiring precision/recall pre-registration (the claim concerns whether any fixed precision/recall can beat self-consistency, so the falsifier is the observed harness-vs-self-consistency score gap, not a pre-registered precision/recall bound).","case":"The target violates std-crit-design clause (1): the mechanism is not stated in measurable quantities. The 'mechanism' field describes the causal story in prose ('false-positive rate on low-error questions cancels or exceeds its true-positive gains') but never gives the critic precision and recall values, the ensemble size k, or the candidate base error rate at which the claimed crossover occurs. k=7 and e~0.10/e~0.35 appear only in prose_notes, not in the mechanism itself, and the critic precision/recall is never specified at all — the design relies on 'verbalized uncertainty calibrated against per-question candidate disagreement' without pre-registering the precision/recall bounds that would make the divergen